From: Refracta user
Date: 2026-07-09
Subject: [PATCH v12] GUI installer: automated mode asks everything up front, then runs unattended

Building on v1-v11. v11 instrumented the GUI installer so the log shows exactly
WHEN each dialog appeared; the log of a real automated run confirmed the UX
problem: after the up-front option/disk dialogs the installer does a long copy
(~3.5 min of rsync) and only THEN asks the bootloader question, the hostname/
username, and the password(s). The user cannot walk away - they return to more
prompts and more waiting.

v12 fixes this for the "Automated btrfs install" path (auto_mode) only. Custom
mode is unchanged.

What changes (auto_mode only):

  - The hostname/username dialog and the password dialog(s) are now asked BEFORE
    the copy, in a single collect phase placed just before the Summary, so the
    Summary is the true final "last chance" gate. Their answers are remembered
    in variables (new_hostname/newname/.../user_newpass/root_newpass) and applied
    unattended in the install tail.
  - The post-copy "Install Bootloader" dialog is skipped: automated mode already
    promises no expert questions, so GRUB is always installed (answer=3).
  - The tail's dialog calls are guarded so auto_mode never re-prompts: the
    username dialog, the hostname-legality check, and set_rootpass/set_userpass
    use the pre-collected values instead of showing a dialog.

How it is done (mechanics):

  - The dialog/collection helpers (clean_log, pass_error, configure_pass,
    username_dialog, fix_hostname, test_hostname) are relocated verbatim to just
    before the Summary. Bash needs a function defined before it is called, and
    these were previously defined only in the tail (after the copy); moving them
    up lets the collect phase call them. Custom mode calls them from the same
    tail sites as before - behaviour is identical, only the definition point
    moved.
  - Passwords: the collect phase pauses xtrace (set +x) around the password
    dialogs so the plain text never reaches the log at all, and remembers each
    password in memory for the tail to apply (where the existing clean_log still
    scrubs the apply-time traces). It deliberately does NOT run clean_log up
    front: clean_log scrubs with `sed -i`, which swaps the log file's inode and
    would detach the script's redirected stderr, silencing the rest of the
    install. As a safety net the collect phase re-attaches stderr
    (exec 2>>"$error_log") after the dialogs in case a mismatched-password retry
    ran pass_error->clean_log.

Changes from v11:
  - refractainstaller-yad: relocate the six dialog/collection helpers above the
    Summary; add an auto_mode collect phase (username + password[s]); skip the
    bootloader dialog in auto_mode (always install GRUB); guard the tail
    username/hostname/password sites so auto_mode applies the collected answers
    without re-prompting. Custom mode unchanged.
  - (refractainstaller CLI and btrfs-disk-lib.sh unchanged from v9/v10/v11.)

---
--- a/usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad
+++ b/usr/bin/refractainstaller-yad
@@ -52,6 +52,86 @@
 
 configfile="/etc/refractainstaller.conf"
 
+# btrfs subvolume layout.
+#
+# The installer LEARNS the real layout from the disk instead of hard-coding it:
+# the disk-setup script writes a small manifest at the btrfs top level
+# (subvolid=5), named by $btrfs_layout_manifest, with one TAB-separated
+# "<subvolume><TAB><mountpoint>" line per subvolume. load_btrfs_layout() reads
+# it into the arrays below, so ANY subvolume scheme works with no edits here.
+#
+# The arrays below are only the FALLBACK used when no manifest is present (e.g.
+# when formatting via the installer's own "btrfs (with subvolumes)" menu).
+btrfs_layout_manifest=".refracta-btrfs-layout"
+btrfs_subvols=( @rootfs @home @var @tmp @snapshots )
+btrfs_subvol_mounts=( "/" "/home" "/var" "/tmp" "/.snapshots" )
+btrfs_root_subvol="@rootfs"   # the subvolume mounted at "/" (overridden by manifest)
+btrfs_layout_source="default" # "manifest", "guessed", or "default" (for messages)
+
+# btrfs_guess_mount SUBVOL
+#   Best-effort mountpoint for a subvolume name when no manifest exists.
+#   Known names are mapped explicitly; unknown "@a_b_c" become "/a/b/c".
+btrfs_guess_mount () {
+	case "$1" in
+		@rootfs|@root|@)  echo "/" ;;
+		@home)            echo "/home" ;;
+		@snapshots)       echo "/.snapshots" ;;
+		@swap)            echo "/swap" ;;
+		@var)             echo "/var" ;;
+		@var_log)         echo "/var/log" ;;
+		@var_cache)       echo "/var/cache" ;;
+		@libvirt_images)  echo "/var/lib/libvirt/images" ;;
+		@tmp)             echo "/tmp" ;;
+		@opt)             echo "/opt" ;;
+		@srv)             echo "/srv" ;;
+		@*)               local _n="${1#@}" ; echo "/${_n//_//}" ;;
+		*)                echo "" ;;
+	esac
+}
+
+# load_btrfs_layout DEVICE
+#   Learn the btrfs subvolume layout of DEVICE by mounting its top level
+#   (subvolid=5) and either (1) reading the layout manifest if present
+#   (authoritative), or (2) discovering the existing subvolumes with
+#   `btrfs subvolume list` and guessing their mountpoints by convention.
+#   Populates btrfs_subvols / btrfs_subvol_mounts (sorted shallow-first so
+#   parent mounts precede children) and btrfs_root_subvol / btrfs_layout_source.
+#   Returns 0 if any subvolumes were found (=> subvol mode), 1 otherwise.
+load_btrfs_layout () {
+	local _dev="$1" _tmp _raw="" _src="default" _rc=1 _sv _mp _i
+	_tmp=$(mktemp -d)
+	mount -o subvolid=5 "$_dev" "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null || { rmdir "$_tmp"; return 1; }
+	if [[ -f "$_tmp/$btrfs_layout_manifest" ]]; then
+		_raw=$(awk -F'\t' '/^[[:space:]]*#/{next} NF<2{next} {print $1"\t"$2}' "$_tmp/$btrfs_layout_manifest")
+		_src="manifest"
+	else
+		_raw=$(btrfs subvolume list "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null | awk '{print $NF}' \
+			| while read -r _s; do
+				[[ "$_s" == */* ]] && continue   # skip nested subvolumes
+				printf '%s\t%s\n' "$_s" "$(btrfs_guess_mount "$_s")"
+			done)
+		_src="guessed"
+	fi
+	umount "$_tmp" 2>/dev/null; rmdir "$_tmp"
+
+	if [[ -n "$_raw" ]]; then
+		btrfs_subvols=(); btrfs_subvol_mounts=()
+		while IFS=$'\t' read -r _ _sv _mp; do
+			[[ -z "$_sv" || -z "$_mp" ]] && continue
+			btrfs_subvols+=("$_sv"); btrfs_subvol_mounts+=("$_mp")
+		done < <(printf '%s\n' "$_raw" | awk -F'\t' 'NF>=2 && $2!="" {d=gsub(/\//,"/",$2); print d"\t"$1"\t"$2}' | sort -n -k1,1)
+		if [[ ${#btrfs_subvols[@]} -gt 0 ]]; then
+			btrfs_root_subvol="@rootfs"
+			for _i in "${!btrfs_subvols[@]}"; do
+				[[ "${btrfs_subvol_mounts[$_i]}" == "/" ]] && btrfs_root_subvol="${btrfs_subvols[$_i]}"
+			done
+			btrfs_layout_source="$_src"
+			_rc=0
+		fi
+	fi
+	return $_rc
+}
+
 if [[ -f $configfile ]]; then
     source $configfile
 else
